item.title: Metals Slip as China Demand Worries Linger
item.description: Base metals and gold prices edged lower in early London trade, as worries around the Chinese economy continued to dominate sentiment.

item.title: Barratt Forward Sales Slide
item.description: Barratt Developments posted an above-forecast adjusted profit of £884 million for the full-year but reported total forward sales sharply below the figure in 2022.

item.title: China Bans iPhone Use for Government Officials at Work
item.description: The directive is the latest step in Beijing’s campaign to cut reliance on foreign technology and could hurt Apple’s business in the country.

item.title: Dollar Should Stay Strong After Tuesday's Steep Gains
item.description: The dollar should hold on to most of Tuesday’s gains, DZ Bank Research said, adding that even if the service purchasing managers surveys are weaker than expected they are “unlikely to trigger a complete reversal of yesterday’s losses in EUR/USD.”

item.title: Eurozone Bond Yields Rise as ECB Looks Set for Higher-for-Longer Rates
item.description: Eurozone government bond yields edged higher after Bundesbank President Joachim Nagel hinted at higher-for-longer interest rates in an interview with German newspaper Handelsblatt, RBC Capital Markets said.

item.title: Norwegian Air Positive on Autumn Sales
item.description: Norwegian Air Shuttle said passenger numbers rose 7.3% in August, despite a storm in Norway and the traffic control issues in the U.K. affecting operations, and added the booking momentum for the months ahead looked positive.

item.title: German Manufacturing Orders Tumble
item.description: New orders at German factories fell 11.7% in July, considerably more than expected, a further indication of declining demand for goods from Europe’s largest economy.

item.title: Chinese Shares End Mixed; Property, Finance Stocks Gain
item.description: Chinese shares ended mixed as traders weighed expectations of more stimulus against continued concerns of an economic slowdown.

item.title: Toyota to Join Global Luxury Car Market With $170,000 Flagship Model
item.description: Toyota thinks the world outside of Japan may finally be ready to embrace its six-figure superluxury flagship car.

item.title: Credit Agricole Takes Ownership of Hiflow
item.description: Credit Agricole’s consumer-finance arm has bought a stake in Hiflow that gives it majority ownership in the vehicle-delivery company and agreed a cooperation deal.

item.title: McConnell Returns to Senate After Health Scares
item.description: Congress’s top doctor says the Senate minority leader didn’t suffer a stroke.

item.title: Chinese Property Stocks Jump Amid Hopes for More Stimulus
item.description: Chinese property stocks jumped amid hopes of more property-market stimulus ahead and a state-owned media report saying Beijing might roll out new measures to shore up the sector.

item.title: As EVs Fill Rental-Car Lots, Drivers Feel Jittery
item.description: The shifting mix of cars means growing pains for travelers unaccustomed to operating electric vehicles.

item.title: Australia's New South Wales State to Raise Coal Royalty Rates
item.description: Australia’s New South Wales state will raise royalty rates to be paid by coal miners there, seeking greater benefit from elevated prices fanned by energy-supply concerns following Russia’s invasion of Ukraine.

item.title: Once Inoculated by Its Nazi Past, Germany Is Becoming a Far-Right Stronghold
item.description: Support for the pro-Russia, anti-immigration Alternative for Germany party has reached records as more voters lose faith in mainstream politics.

item.title: Rising Rents Hitting Suburbs Hardest
item.description: The recent migration of families from major cities is starting to look permanent.

item.title: How Russia's Blockade of Black Sea Ports Is Hitting Ukraine's Economy
item.description: Since its invasion of Ukraine, Russia has been attacking Ukraine’s economy by taking aim at its crucial ports on the Black Sea. WSJ’s Shelby Holliday explains how Moscow’s strategy has worked, and what the West is doing to try and counter its blockade.

item.title: Economists Cut Singapore 2023 Growth Forecast
item.description: Experts surveyed by Singapore’s central bank again cut projections for the country’s economic growth this year, after the expansion recorded in the second quarter widely missed expectations.

item.title: European Rail Giants Fight for Slice of U.S. High-Speed Train Line
item.description: Siemens and Alstom are vying to supply trains for a planned Los Angeles to Las Vegas link.

item.title: British chip designer Arm is targeting a valuation of more than $52 billion from what is expected to be the largest IPO this year, according to the company's latest regulatory filing.
item.description: British chip designer Arm is targeting a valuation of more than $52 billion from what is expected to be the largest IPO this year, according to the company’s latest regulatory filing.
